    \"target_achievement\": 0.75,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"Conceptually elegant and historically grounded (Schulze & Winterstein 1899). The direct guanylation of ornithine's \u03b4-amino group by cyanamide is well-established chemistry. However, the pathway as drawn requires ornithine as an external input without specifying its prebiotic source within this 2-step pathway. Tsubokura et al. 2014 showed 95% yield with Sc(OTf)\u2083 catalyst, but no strictly prebiotic demonstration exists. Environmental progression is limited (Surface only). The selectivity for \u03b4-amino over \u03b1-amino guanylation under prebiotic conditions is unaddressed.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify ornithine source explicitly within pathway\", \"Address regioselectivity of guanylation (\u03b4 vs \u03b1 amino group)\", \"Include mineral catalyst for the guanylation step\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.60,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"Ambitious pathway attempting full autotrophic synthesis from CO\u2082. The hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192surface environmental flow is well-structured. However, two reactions are severely problematic: rxn_004 (pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate in one step) requires multiple rTCA intermediates that are collapsed into one node, and rxn_006 (glutamate \u2192 ornithine) requires multiple biosynthetic steps (N-acetylation, transamination, deacetylation) with no prebiotic precedent. The literature explicitly notes that modern biosynthesis requires at least 8 enzymatic steps from glutamate to arginine. Rxn_002 (formate \u2192 pyruvate) is also ambitious as a single step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_002\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Decompose rxn_004 into explicit rTCA intermediates (oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, succinate, succinyl-CoA analog)\", \"Replace rxn_006 with a plausible prebiotic route to ornithine (e.g., Strecker synthesis from glutamic semialdehyde)\", \"Add intermediate steps for formate-to-pyruvate conversion\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.40\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.60,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.45,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.56,\n      \"feedback\": \"The prebiotic urea cycle analog is an intellectually interesting pathway. The carbamoylation of ornithine by cyanate (rxn_016) is well-supported by Juarez et al. 2021 and avoids the biological requirement for carbamoyl phosphate. However, rxn_017 (citrulline \u2192 arginine) is described in the literature as 'entirely hypothetical' with 'no experimental demonstration.' In biology this conversion requires argininosuccinate synthetase + lyase with ATP activation. The prebiotic equivalent is not specified. The pathway correctly represents current knowledge but is not yet experimentally validated.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Propose a specific mechanism for citrulline-to-arginine conversion (e.g., condensation with aspartate analog + elimination)\", \"Consider whether cyanamide could serve as both condensing and guanylating agent to drive this step\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.40\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.35,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.40,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.50,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.35,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.37,\n      \"feedback\": \"Based on Fujioka et al. 2009, which detected only 0.32 \u03bcmol arginine (vs 60.7 \u03bcmol alanine) under supercritical CO\u2082/H\u2082O conditions. The mechanism was never elucidated, the starting materials (hydroxylamine, pyruvic acid) are themselves complex intermediates, and the result has not been independently replicated. The pathway is correctly included as a data point but cannot be considered a viable route. Hydroxylamine is listed as a starting material but is itself prebiotically questionable at the concentrations required.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Downgrade this to a supporting observation rather than a primary pathway\", \"Investigate whether supercritical conditions could enhance other pathway steps instead\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.40\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.52,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.42,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.53,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway combines the weaknesses of P3 (problematic rxn_004 and rxn_006) with P4 (hypothetical rxn_017). While the environmental flow (Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical) is well-structured, two critical bottlenecks remain: the prebiotic conversion of glutamate to ornithine and citrulline to arginine. Both lack experimental support.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Focus on strengthening the ornithine source independently before building this extended pathway\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.55,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.58,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway has a conceptual problem: rxn_014 produces guanidine from HCN + NH\u2083 (Lohrmann 1972, well-supported), but guanidine is not the same as cyanamide for guanylation purposes. Cyanamide (H\u2082N-C\u2261N) is electrophilic at carbon and reacts with amines to form guanidines. Free guanidine (already trisubstituted nitrogen) does not directly guanylate ornithine. The pathway would need an additional activation step or a different mechanism. Guanidine is listed as mol_018 but rxn_013 uses cyanamide (mol_013), not guanidine, creating a disconnect.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify how guanidine feeds into arginine formation \u2014 guanidine needs activation to serve as guanylating agent\", \"Consider a condensation pathway: guanidine + glutamic semialdehyde \u2192 arginine via reductive coupling\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.81,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid pathway integrates hydrothermal 