icitly notes the mechanism was not elucidated. This pathway adds completeness to the network but has very low confidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Fix hydroxylamine stoichiometry to include an oxygen/nitrogen oxide source\", \"Downgrade this pathway to supporting/speculative status\", \"Note the 200\u00d7 yield gap vs. alanine in Fujioka's experiment\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.68,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.70,\n      \"feedback\": \"An ambitious convergence of cyanosulfidic \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde chemistry with hydrothermal glutamate production. The convergence concept is sound but the pathway inherits the weaknesses of rxn_012 (compressed rTCA). The \u03b2-aminopropionaldehyde branch is strong; the glutamate branch is moderate.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen the rTCA steps or source glutamate from Miller-Urey chemistry instead\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed and thoroughly literature-grounded synthesis network for one of prebiotic chemistry's most challenging targets. The network excels in several areas: (1) Excellent literature alignment \u2014 the primary pathways faithfully implement Patel et al. 2015's cyanosulfidic chemistry and the classical ornithine + cyanamide guanylation, with appropriate citations throughout. (2) Strong network topology with 23 molecules, 19 reactions, 5 well-connected hub molecules, and genuine convergent pathways. (3) Good environmental progression from hydrothermal (CO2 reduction, HCN generation) through surface (photochemistry, Cu(I) catalysis) to biochemical (hydrolysis, clay concentration). (4) Honest inclusion of the Fujioka trace route alongside the stronger pathways shows completeness without overclaiming.\\n\\nKey weaknesses: (1) rxn_012 compresses multiple rTCA steps into one reaction, which is chemically misleading. (2) rxn_014 (glutamic acid \u2192 glutamic semialdehyde) lacks prebiotic precedent and is essentially an enzymatic step. (3) rxn_019 has incorrect stoichiometry for hydroxylamine formation. (4) The cyanamide synthesis (rxn_004) from HCN + NH3 photochemistry needs more mechanistic detail. (5) No pathway addresses chirality.\\n\\nThe network correctly identifies the fundamental arginine challenge (guanidinium installation) and implements the two most promising solutions from the literature. The montmorillonite concentration mechanism is a thoughtful addition. The three approved pathways (P1, P4, P7) all follow the cyanosulfidic route, which is indeed the most experimentally substantiated approach. Overall, this network represents a strong synthesis of current knowledge and earns approval despite the known limitations of prebiotic arginine chemistry.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.86,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.82\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_004": 0.65, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.9, "rxn_007": 0.8, "rxn_008": 0.85, "rxn_009": 0.8, "rxn_010": 0.8}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.81, "pathway_coherence": 0.85, "environmental_progression": 0.82, "target_achievement": 0.78, "overall_confidence": 0.82, "feedback": "This is the strongest pathway, directly implementing the Patel et al. 2015 cyanosulfidic route. The Cu(I)-catalyze