          \"rxn_014\": 0.60,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.73,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.68,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.70,\n            \"feedback\": \"HCN oligomer hydrolysis producing ornithine (rxn_014) is the weakest link. While Ferris et al. 1978 showed HCN polymer hydrolysis produces various amino acids and diamino acids, ornithine specifically is not well-documented as a major product of this route. The literature identifies citrulline-like intermediates from HCN polymer hydrolysis, but the direct production of ornithine in useful yields is uncertain. The subsequent cyanamide guanylation is sound.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Provide specific citation for ornithine from HCN polymer hydrolysis\", \"Consider replacing with citrulline as an intermediate, which has better HCN polymer precedent (Ferris et al. 1978)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.81,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"Nearly identical to P1 but explicitly includes serpentinization as the H2/NH3 source. The serpentinization step is well-supported by 